"Jugsujinda A., Lindau C.W., Delaune R.D., Patrick Jr. W.H.","Effect of soil oxidants KNO3, MnO2, and air on methane production in flooded rice soil suspension",1998,"Water, Air, and Soil Pollution","105","3-4",,"677","684",,,10.1023/A:1004985131870,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032474739&partnerID=40&md5=89e1df01c73adad18eaf3d7f58876025","Wetland Biogeochemistry Institute, Nuclear Science Center, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA 70803, United States","Jugsujinda, A., Wetland Biogeochemistry Institute, Nuclear Science Center, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA 70803, United States; Lindau, C.W., Wetland Biogeochemistry Institute, Nuclear Science Center, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA 70803, United States; Delaune, R.D., Wetland Biogeochemistry Institute, Nuclear Science Center, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA 70803, United States; Patrick Jr., W.H., Wetland Biogeochemistry Institute, Nuclear Science Center, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA 70803, United States","To determine effective means to reduce methane (CH4) production from flooded rice soil, laboratory measurements were made on methane (CH4) formation in a Crowley silt loam as affected by the addition of potassium nitrate (KNO3), manganese dioxide (MnO2), and air (O2) under flooded conditions. In the experiment, oxidants were added to the soil prior to flooding at the rate of 300 and 1000 ppm O2 equivalent. Methane production was measured over a 32 d incubation period. Potassium nitrate added at rates of 300 and 1000 ppm O2 equivalent reduced CH4 production by 100% and MnO2, at 300 and 1000 ppm O2 equivalent, significantly decreased CH4 formation approximately 20% and 98-99% over the 32 d period, respectively compared to controls. Air addition did not significantly affect CH4 formation.","Air pollution; Global warming; Greenhouse gas; Methane formation","Manganese oxide; Potassium nitrate; Air; Floods; Global warming; Manganese compounds; Methane; Potassium compounds; Silt; Soil pollution; Air pollution; manganese dioxide; methane; potassium nitrate; methane; paddy soil; pollution control; soil amendment; air pollution; article; controlled study; environmental monitoring; global climate; greenhouse effect; oxidation reduction reaction; rice; soil pollution",,"manganese dioxide, 1313-13-9; methane, 74-82-8; potassium nitrate, 7757-79-1",,,,"Adamsen, A.P.S., King, G.M., (1993) Appli. and Environ. Microbiol., 59, p. 485; Alperin, M.J., Reeburgh, R.S., Geological Observation Suupporting Anaerobic Methane Oxidation (1984) Microbial Growth on C-1 Compounds, pp. 282-289. , R. L. Craword and R. S. Hanson (eds.), American Society for Microbiology, Washington, D. C; Blake, D.R., Rowland, E.S., (1988) Science, 239, p. 1129; Bouwman, A.F., Background (1990) Soils and the Greenhouse Effect, pp. 25-192. , A. F. Bouwman (ed.), John Wiley & Sons, New York; Bouwman, A.F., (1991) Biogeochem., 15, p. 65; Cicerone, R.J., Oremland, R.S., (1988) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 2, p. 299; Connel, W.E., Patrick Jr., W.H., (1968) Science, 159, p. 86; Crutzen, P.J., (1991) Nature, 350, p. 380; Jugsujinda, A., DeLaune, R.D., Sulaeman, E., Lindau, C.W., Pezeshki, S.R., (1996) Water, Air, and Soil Pollut., 87, p. 345; Jugsujinda, A., DeLaune, D., Lindau, C.W., (1995) Commun. Soil Sci. Plant Anal. bf, 26, p. 2449; Jugsujinda, A., Patrick Jr., W.H., (1996) Comm. Soil Sci. Plant Anal., 27, p. 7; Lindau, C.W., (1994) Soil Biol. Biochem., 26, p. 353; Masscheleyn, P.H., DeLaune, R.D., Patrick Jr., W.H., (1993) Chemosphere, 26, p. 251; Murase, J., Kimura, M., (1994) Soil Sci. Plant Nutr., 40, p. 57; Murase, J., Kimura, M., (1994) Soil Sci. Plant Nutr., 40, p. 505; Murase, J., Kimura, M., (1994) Soil Sci. Plant Nutr., 40, p. 647; (1985) SAS/STAT User's Guide, Release 6.03, , SAS Inst. Cary. N.C; Yaki, K., Chairoj, P., Tsuruta, H., Cholitkul, W., Minami, K., (1994) Soil Sci. Plant. Nutr., 40, p. 29","Jugsujinda, A.; Wetland Biogeochem